  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The locality is again described ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "as beyond Jordan",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see on ver. 1), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and in the land of Moab.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This designates the region elsewhere called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Arboth Moab -",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the Plains of Moab (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 22:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 34:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), the region on the east of the Jordan, opposite to Jericho, now known as the region of Kerak (Burckhardt, 'Syria,' p. 377, etc.; Robinson, 'Bib. Res.,\" 2:569). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Began",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; rather ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "set himself to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Hebrew word signifies to undertake, to betake one's self to, and so to begin It is variously rendered in the Authorized Version (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 18:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"taken it upon me;\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 2:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"was content,\" had made up his mind; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 12:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"it pleased;\" 17:39,\"assayed,\" etc.). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To declare",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". make clear, explain, expound (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Habakkuk 2:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"make plain \"). The Hebrew word here used (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "בָאַר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") signifies primarily to cut or dig, then to cut into, to grave, and then to cut or dig out so as to make evident, to declare, to make plain. What Moses set himself to do, then, was not to publish a new law, but to make plain to the people the Law already promulgated, to set forth clearly and pointedly what they were required by the Law to be and to do. This explains more fully the \"spake\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "דִבֶּר",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of ver. 3. This exposition of the Law was designed specially for the sake of those who, at the time the Law was first promulgated, either were not born or were incapable of understanding it (Grotius). The expression used by Moses plainly indicates that this book was not intended to furnish a second code of laws different from the former, but simply to explain and enforce what had before been enjoined. Deuteronomy 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To the description of the ground to which the following addresses refer, there is appended an allusion to the not less significant time when Moses delivered them, viz., \"on the first of the eleventh month in the fortieth year,\" consequently towards the end of his life, after the conclusion of the divine lawgiving; so that he was able to speak \"according to all that Jehovah had given him in commandment unto them\" (the Israelites), namely, in the legislation of the former books, which is always referred to in this way (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 5:29-30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 6:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The time was also significant, from the fact that Sihon and Og, the kings of the Amorites, had then been slain. By giving a victory over these mighty kings, the Lord had begun to fulfil His promises (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 2:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and had thereby laid Israel under the obligation to love, gratitude, and obedience (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:21-35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The suffix in הכּתו refers to Moses, who had smitten the Amorites at the command and by the power of Jehovah. According to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 12:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 13:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Edrei was the second capital of Og, and it is as such that it is mentioned, and not as the place where Og was defeated (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The omission of the copula ו before בּאדרעי is to be accounted for from the oratorical character of the introduction to the addresses which follow. Edrei is the present Dra (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 21:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the description of the locality is again resumed in the words \"beyond the Jordan,\" and still further defined by the expression \"in the land of Moab;\" and the address itself is introduced by the clause, \"Moses took in hand to expound this law,\" which explains more fully the דּבּר (spake) of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"In the land of Moab\" is a rhetorical and general expression for \"in the Arboth Moab.\" הואיל does not mean to begin, but to undertake, to take in hand, with the subordinate idea sometimes of venturing, or daring (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 18:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), sometimes of a bold resolution: here it denotes an undertaking prompted by internal impulse. Instead of being construed with the infinitive, it is construed rhetorically here with the finite verb without the copula (cf. Ges. 143, 3, b). בּאר probably signified to dig in the Kal; but this is not used. In the Piel it means to explain (διασαφῆσαι, explanare, lxx, Vulg.), never to engrave, or stamp, not even here nor in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 27:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Habakkuk 2:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Here it signifies \"to expound this law clearly,\" although the exposition was connected with an earnest admonition to preserve and obey it. \"This\" no doubt refers to the law expounded in what follows; but substantially it is no other than the law already given in the earlier books. \"Substantially there is throughout but one law\" (Schultz). That the book of Deuteronomy was not intended to furnish a new or second law, is as evident as possible from the word בּאר. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]